> for the record, the dinosaurs that had the big frills and poison spit? It never had the frills or poison spit.

We don't know what dinosaurs had, or really what they looked like, because all we have are bones. That was the point of that dinosaur.

In the book a huge, huge theme is that Hammond is putting money before all else. He rushes everything and ignores potential problems to get his park open, and he wants it open no matter what.

It doesn't really make it to the movies where he's more sympathetic and the problems of the park aren't brought up so much, but the venom spitting dino is just one example for that of many.

They had no idea it could do that either, until suddenly it blinded a keeper. His vets have tried to remove it's venom sacs but can't seem to find them, and each individual dinosaur is expensive so he won't allow a full kill and dissect. Just bringing back an individual species is ungodly expensive, so he refuses to stop making them either because they *are* a dinosaur he can exhibit. So he just sort of has them in the park even though they could blind a child.

The book is not subtle, and is full of stuff like that. Nedry is such a dick because of it for example. Hammond employed him to make the park systems, which are hugely automated so he can run it with a skeleton crew for cheap. But since Hammond never told him what it was actually *for* (and he definitely didn't tell him lives would depend on it) it's full of hundreds of bugs and instead of paying him like a reasonable person Hammond basically blackmails him by threatening bad reviews into coming back and upgrading it for free.
